---
title: Tourongo — Concurrency & Double-Booking Prevention
---

sequenceDiagram
    participant A as Thread A (User A)
    participant B as Thread B (User B)
    participant DB as PostgreSQL

    Note over A,DB: Scenario: 1 seat left (seatsReserved=9, maxCapacity=10). Two users book simultaneously.

    A->>DB: BEGIN TRANSACTION
    A->>DB: SELECT * FROM tour_occurrences WHERE id=42 FOR UPDATE
    Note over DB: Row-level WRITE LOCK acquired by Thread A ✅
    B->>DB: BEGIN TRANSACTION
    B->>DB: SELECT * FROM tour_occurrences WHERE id=42 FOR UPDATE
    Note over DB: Thread B BLOCKS — waiting for lock ⏳
    Note over DB: Lock timeout = 2000ms

    A->>DB: Read: seatsReserved=9, maxCapacity=10
    Note over A: 9 + 1 = 10 ≤ 10 ✅ proceed
    A->>DB: UPDATE tour_occurrences SET seatsReserved=10 WHERE id=42
    A->>DB: INSERT INTO bookings (status=PendingPayment, ...)
    A->>DB: COMMIT ← lock released ✅

    Note over DB: Thread B now gets the lock
    B->>DB: Read: seatsReserved=10, maxCapacity=10 (sees committed value)
    Note over B: 10 + 1 = 11 > 10 ❌ CONFLICT
    B-->>API: throw SeatUnavailableException
    B->>DB: ROLLBACK

    Note over A,DB: Result: exactly 1 booking, no overbook

    Note over A,DB: Deadlock Prevention (reschedule scenario)
    Note over A,DB: Always lock TWO occurrences in ascending ID order
    Note over A,DB: Thread A locks ID=10 then ID=20
    Note over A,DB: Thread B also locks ID=10 then ID=20
    Note over A,DB: Same order → Thread B blocks on ID=10 → no deadlock

    Note over A,DB: Optimistic Lock (@Version on Booking)
    Note over A,DB: PaymentTimeoutJob vs Stripe webhook race:
    Note over A,DB: One wins → updates @Version → other gets OptimisticLockException
    Note over A,DB: Caught + logged → booking state remains consistent
